{
  "answer": "Step 1: Short-Run Effects of Expansionary Monetary Policy in the AD-AS Model - An expansionary monetary policy (e.g., increasing money supply) shifts the aggregate demand (AD) curve to the right. This leads to higher output (real GDP) and higher price levels (inflation) in the short run. The increase in output reduces unemployment temporarily due to higher demand for labor. Step 2: Short-Run Phillips Curve Relationship - The short-run Phillips curve shows an inverse relationship between inflation and unemployment. The initial reduction in unemployment occurs because workers and firms adjust slowly to the higher inflation (expectations are sticky). The size of the unemployment response depends on the slope of the short-run aggregate supply curve (parameter 'a'). Step 3: Long-Run Adjustment - In the long run, expectations adjust. Workers and firms realize inflation is higher, so they demand higher wages and prices. This shifts the short-run aggregate supply (SRAS) curve left, returning output to its natural level (potential GDP) but at a higher price level. Unemployment returns to its natural rate. Step 4: Long-Run Phillips Curve - The long-run Phillips curve is vertical at the natural rate of unemployment, showing no tradeoff between inflation and unemployment in the long run. This aligns with the natural-rate hypothesis: any attempt to reduce unemployment below its natural rate via inflation only works temporarily until expectations adjust."
}

